// Aztec / Mexica gods — the 12 canonical deities of the Mexica-Aztec
// pantheon of Tenochtitlán c. 1325-1521 CE — SEO funnel.
// /gab44/aztec-gods (index) + /gab44/aztec-gods/{slug}.
//
// The eighth great pantheon on gab44 after Olympians, Norse, Hindu Devas,
// Egyptian, Celtic, Orishas, and Mesopotamian. The FIRST pre-Columbian
// pantheon on the site — closing the structural geographic gap of having
// covered Europe (Greek, Norse, Celtic), Africa (Egyptian, Orisha),
// Mesopotamia, and the Indian subcontinent (Hindu) without any presence
// from the Americas. This is also the youngest fully-documented great
// pantheon (c. 1325 CE Mexica founding of Tenochtitlán) and the only
// one for which we have first-generation conquistador-and-friar
// ethnography written by people who *met the priests of the religion*
// (Bernardino de Sahagún interviewed surviving Mexica elders in Nahuatl
// in the 1550s-1580s and the Florentine Codex is the result).
//
// Three families × 4 deities:
//  - Primordial & Cosmic (Ometeotl / Quetzalcoatl / Tezcatlipoca /
//    Tonatiuh — the cosmic duality + the two great cosmic rivals + the
//    current Fifth Sun).
//  - Earth, Water & Fertility (Tlaloc / Chalchiuhtlicue / Coatlicue /
//    Xochiquetzal — rain-storm / lake-river / serpent-earth-mother /
//    flower-love).
//  - War, Death & Renewal (Huitzilopochtli / Mictlantecuhtli / Xipe
//    Totec / Mixcoatl — Mexica solar-war-patron / lord of Mictlan /
//    flayed-lord-of-spring / cloud-serpent-hunt).
//
// Source-honest from the Florentine Codex (Bernardino de Sahagún's
// Historia general de las cosas de Nueva España, 12 books in Nahuatl
// and Spanish, c. 1545-1590, compiled from interviews with surviving
// Mexica priests and elders — the single most-important ethnographic
// source for any Native American religion), the Codex Borgia
// (pre-conquest ritual-calendar codex, c. 1450 CE), the Codex
// Mendoza (1541, post-conquest tribute-list with deity-panels), the
// Codex Magliabechiano (post-conquest ritual handbook), the Codex
// Borbonicus (early-post-conquest divinatory almanac), the Anales de
// Cuauhtitlán (Nahuatl historical chronicle), the Leyenda de los
// Soles (cosmogonic narrative of the five suns), Hernán Cortés's
// Cartas de Relación (1519-1525) to Charles V, Bernal Díaz del
// Castillo's Historia Verdadera (c. 1568), Diego Durán's Historia
// de las Indias de Nueva España (c. 1581), Toribio de Benavente
// (Motolinía)'s Memoriales, Miguel León-Portilla's *Aztec Thought
// and Culture* (Oklahoma 1963) and *The Broken Spears* (1962),
// Inga Clendinnen's *Aztecs: An Interpretation* (Cambridge 1991 —
// the canonical English-language interpretive monograph), David
// Carrasco's *City of Sacrifice* (Beacon 1999) and *Religions of
// Mesoamerica* (Harper 1990), Eduardo Matos Moctezuma's archaeology
// of the Templo Mayor (the great Mexica double-temple discovered
// under downtown Mexico City in 1978 and excavated continuously
// since), Alfredo López Austin's *The Human Body and Ideology*
// (Utah 1988), and the corpus of Nahuatl-language poetry preserved
// in the Cantares Mexicanos and the Romances de los Señores de la
// Nueva España.
//
// Shadow-honest: the Spanish conquest 1519-1521 and the deliberate
// systematic destruction of pre-Hispanic religious material (the
// burning of the Texcoco library of Nezahualcoyotl, the destruction
// of every codex in the Templo Mayor precinct, the demolition of
// the Templo Mayor itself with the Cathedral of Mexico City
// deliberately built on its rubble); Friar Diego de Landa's
// auto-da-fé at Maní in 1562 in which thousands of Maya codices
// were burned (only 4 pre-conquest Maya codices survived, none of
// which are Mexica); the use of human-sacrifice as conquest-
// justification (when European warfare killed orders of magnitude
// more people in the same century and the Spanish themselves
// burned Mexica nobles alive in cathedral plazas as "auto-da-fé");
// the 16th-19th c. "Black Legend" framing that presented Mexica
// religion as uniquely savage; the 19th-c. romantic-indigenist
// reduction of all pre-Hispanic religion to "noble savage"; the
// 20th-c. Mexica revival (danza azteca, neo-Mexica spirituality,
// the Mexicayotl movement of Rodolfo Nieva and Maximino Sánchez
// from the 1950s onward) which has sometimes flattened the
// distinct Mexica/Toltec/Maya/Mixtec/Zapotec traditions into a
// generic "ancient Mexican" mysticism; the New Age co-option of
// Quetzalcoatl into a generic "ascended master" archetype divorced
// from the specific Toltec-Mexica narrative; the Erich-von-Däniken
// "ancient aliens built the pyramids" pseudoarchaeology that has
// erased Mesoamerican architectural and astronomical achievement;
// the ongoing question of repatriation of Mexica artifacts from
// European museums (the Penacho de Moctezuma — the feathered
// headdress in the Weltmuseum Vienna which Mexico has formally
// requested back since 1991 and Austria has formally refused); the
// modern Mexican school-curriculum bias that has presented the
// Mexica as the "default ancestor" of all Mexicans while erasing
// the c. 60 other indigenous groups still living in modern Mexico;
// the conflation of "Aztec" (a 19th-c. coinage by Alexander von
// Humboldt) with the self-designation "Mexica" (the actual name
// the people used); the controversial 2017-2020 archaeological
// reinterpretation of the human-sacrifice scale at Templo Mayor
// (tzompantli skull-rack discoveries) and the still-ongoing
// debate among Mesoamericanists about how to honor the religion
// without sanitizing its difficult-for-modern-sensibilities
// elements.

